Introduction

Here, we start working on the report, based on the TOC. As the report is in English, Ill write this in English as well.

Right now, this covers simple explorations of questions 1 and 2.

Some things to note:

  • Weighted counts are NOT rounded to the nearest integer. This means that if we were to create a table of, say, how many respondents picked option 1 for question 1, it could say something like 408.5.
  • Theres no guarantee that proportions add up to 100!

Both of these can be fixed by rounding at some point, preferrably just before a table/figure thats shown is generated. Let me know if this is an issue.

At this point, all tables and figures use labels from the Finnish data set. If you can give me a list of preferred labels to use for the English version, I can modify these so that theyre used.

The first to go is question 1. Lets check that out.

data <- read_sav("/home/arto/Data/mediatrust/Combined.sav")
data_sel <- data #%>%
  #dplyr::select(country, uuid_no, uuid_se, uuid_de, uuid_fi, age, age_group, gender, gender_fi, Q15_no, Q15_se, Q15_de, Q15_fi, uuid_fi, weight, starts_with("Q1_"))
data_swe <- data_sel %>% dplyr::filter(country == 1)
data_den <- data_sel %>% dplyr::filter(country == 2)
data_nor <- data_sel %>% dplyr::filter(country == 3)
data_fin <- data_sel %>% dplyr::filter(country == 4)

svy_swe <- svydesign(ids = ~uuid_se, weights = ~weight, data = data_sel %>% dplyr::filter(country == 1))
svy_den <- svydesign(ids = ~uuid_de, weights = ~weight, data = data_sel %>% dplyr::filter(country == 2))
svy_nor <- svydesign(ids = ~uuid_no, weights = ~weight, data = data_sel %>% dplyr::filter(country == 3))
svy_fin <- svydesign(ids = ~uuid_fi, weights = ~weight, data = data_sel %>% dplyr::filter(country == 4))

total_swe <- 1025
total_den <- 1000
total_nor <- 1045
total_fin <- 1093

q2_tableframe_swe <- summarize_q(data_swe, "Q2", c(1:12), svy_swe, total_swe, q2_labels, 2) %>%
  dplyr::mutate(Kysymys = labels_for_media(Kysymys)) %>%
  dplyr::rename(`News source` = Kysymys) %>%
  dplyr::select(-Keskiarvo)

p2_swe <- q2_tableframe_swe %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = `News source`, y = Yes)) +
    geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
    lims(y = c(0, 100)) +
    coord_flip() +

All together

News sources

The patterns are roughly similar: in all countries, news media websites are the most important news sources, followed by television. Radio and social media are approximately equally important. Paper newspapers are more important for Finns than others.

p2_swe + (p2_den + theme(axis.text.y=element_blank())) + p2_nor + (p2_fin + theme(axis.text.y=element_blank())) + plot_layout(guide = "collect") & 
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

Frequency of use

What really surprises me here is that nobody seems to regularly read tabloid newspapers. Then again, Wikipedia says that on average, Iltalehti has ~170 000 readers, which I guess kinda fits with the data here.
